        Blair Pickerell calls it a day on lengthy fund career

        08 July 2015
         
        Category: News, Asia, Global
          
        By Asia Asset Management
    









0 Recommend















	Asia fund veteran Blair Pickerell is stepping down from his position at Nikko Asset Management on August 1. In doing so, he is closing the door on a long and accomplished 30-year career, having had stints at Jardine Matheson/Jardine Fleming, HSBC, Morgan Stanley, and Nikko Asset Management. 

	Mr. Pickerell will remain active non-executively, having accepted an offer to be an independent director at Principal Financial Group, effective August 17 this year, amongst other positions.

	“After three decades of working long hours for several large corporations, I have reached the stage when I should be spending more time doing things that I enjoy and less time stuck behind an office desk,” he said in a farewell note to friends and colleagues.

	Among his various stints in asset management, he was instrumental in breaking into the Taiwan market for Jardine Fleming in the mid-80s, building a presence from the ground up: today, Taiwan is a key market for the firm. He had shorter stints at Morgan Stanley and HSBC.

	But he says he will not entirely leave the industry altogether: “"Semi-retire" is probably a better description, for I suppose it is not easy to go from 90 miles-per-hour to "zero" in one fell swoop. I plan to continue to follow developments in the business world and to sit on a few boards and committees,” he said in the note.

	Part of him being active is remaining as a non-executive director at Dah Sing Financial Holdings, as a member of the international advisory board of SEBI (Securities and Exchange Board of India), and undertaking the position of independent director at Principal, which will become effective on August 17.

	Speaking of his non-executive role at Principal, he said: “They [Principal] serve 19.5 million clients from offices in 18 countries, including several here in Asia. This will require me to visit the US around five times per year to attend board meetings.”      

	Mr. Pickerell admitted that there is a possibility that he will look into undertaking more directorship positions in the future, but said that in order to maintain work from interfering into his new life, which includes hiking, golf, and gardening; he has set a goal of “being busy with such [non-executive] activities only around 40-50% of the time.”  

	After receiving his MBA from Harvard and being hired by Jardine Matheson to set up their Jardine Fleming Taiwan Office in 1984, Mr. Pickerell pioneered the mutual fund in Taiwan, first selling to expatriates, then to locals, then eventually convincing Taiwan banks to act as intermediaries to sell his fund.

	Proficient in Mandarin Chinese, he did not have to overcome the language barrier. As a result, he transformed the mutual fund from an offshore product into a popular choice among retail investors in Taiwan, concurrently helping JF become a monopoly player in the market. In 2011, Mr. Pickerell also spearheaded the US$600 million Huaan Innovation Fund, the first open-ended mutual fund to be introduced in China. Managed by the local Huaan financial firm, the fund invested in RMB-denominated class A-Shares.







